exhibiting persistent modulation along the -direction. Note
that, as compared to the early epoch , the
modulation wave-number has increased twice  asymptotically.

The coupling functions at higher massive levels would be governed
by two qualitatively different contributions. These coupling
functions are extractable from expanding the product of two 
boundary states Eq.() in powers of closed string
oscillator levels. For the first massive level modes, we have seen
in Eq.() that the couplings are quadratic
products among the coefficient functions (
) up to level-2. Likewise, for a generic massive
level mode, the coupling would be quadratic products among the
coefficient functions, now involving higher-level ones. Expanding
the products, we see that the coupling function comprises of two
kind of contributions: the one depending on  (e.g. most of
Eq.() in the case of the first massive level
modes) and the one independent of  (e.g. products among the
first parts of  in the case of
the first massive level modes). As the first type of contributions
depends on , there will always be a singularity at 
. The second type of contributions is non-singular,
generally increasing as , and hence is
qualitatively analogous to the behavior of the couplings for
homogeneous tachyon rolling.

A remark is in order. So far, we have focused primarily on
constructing the boundary state Eq.() itself. It
might well be that some components of the boundary state
Eq.() are BRST exact, viz. couple only to
off-shell or unphysical closed string states. In that case,
recalling that the boundary state Eq.() acts as a
source to the closed string field equation Eq.(), the
BRST exact components would not be contributing to on-shell closed
string processes, such as closed string radiation out of decaying
D-brane. Whether there indeed exists BRST exact components and, if
so, which modes (and their time-dependent coefficient functions)
belong to them are pertinent questions to be examined in case one
needs to study on-shell processes. In this work, we will leave the
issue aside for future study.

Turing on Electric and Magnetic Fields 
With the physics motivation addressed in section 1, we extend the
analysis of section 2 and construct a boundary state for an
unstable D-brane with electric and magnetic fields turned on.

Rolling of Modulated Tachyon under Electric Flux 
We shall now consider turning on a constant  electric field
on the D25-brane world-volume, and study rolling of the spatially
modulated tachyon field. As is well-known, the electric field
induces fundamental string constituents on the D25-brane
world-volume. If the tachyon field were spatially homogeneous, the
induced string charge density (which is given by the electric
displacement field) would be homogeneous over the D25-brane
world-volume as well. On the other hand, if the tachyon field were
spatially modulated, the induced string charge density would be
modulated accordingly and are driven to evolve as the tachyon
rolls down to the potential minimum. In such a circumstance, an
interesting and potentially important question is whether the
displacement field flux can possibly get squeezed into (an array
of) thin flux tubes. If so, adding spatial modulation on a
decaying D-brane would be a new way of manufacturing a
macroscopically large, fundamental closed string!

With such motivation, consider turning on the world-volume
electric field along -direction .
With tachyon modulation along
-direction, this amounts to a fluid of fundamental strings,
whose macroscopic configuration is stretched along -direction
and charge density varies across -direction. As prescribed in
the work, the corresponding boundary state is
obtainable by a sequence of T-dual map, boost by , and inverse
T-dual map, all along the -direction. Denote the new
coordinates as 's and the new string oscillators as 
's. Starting from Eq.(), the
new boundary state would again be expressible as:

