respectively, which is opposite to what we have found for the case
with pure electric field Eq.(). The behavior of the
fundamental string charge and current densities can be read from
Fig. and Fig., respectively. Since 
 at , the charge density is initially zero
everywhere, but then starts to get polarized as the tachyon rolls
down the potential hill.

Intuitively, such a behavior can be understood as follows. As one
can readily see from the gauge invariance 
, , the magnetic
field on a D-brane world-volume induces fundamental string current  density.
 However, when the tachyon field is at the
bottom of its potential and the D-brane disappears, there is
nowhere for the string current to flow. Therefore, the region of
the D-brane world-volume where the tachyon is near the bottom of
the potential acts just like an insulator for an electric current.
In our situation, as the modulated tachyon evolves, the regions
around  () behave as insulators while
those near  () behave as conductors
for the string current. Thus, our system is analogous to a series
of capacitors injected with a non-zero electric current, in which
electric charge starts to accumulate at the edges of the
conductors. The polarization of the fundamental string charge  density is induced in this way. When the system reaches
the critical time, the current density develops a delta-function
singularity, leading to a configuration with a polarized
fundamental string - anti-fundamental string pair near the
critical time.


Effective Field Theory Approach 

It is also of interest to compare the results obtained from the
boundary-state approach with those from other approaches. In this
section, we analyze the D-brane decay in the effective field
theory approach, extending previous results to
the case with inhomogeneous tachyon rolling. Consider the
world-volume Lagrangian of an unstable D-brane:
 
where  is a tachyon potential and  is a function of
 
normalized such that . The energy-momentum tensor
 and the Kalb-Ramond current tensor  are
obtainable by replacing , 
 in the Lagrangian Eq.() and expanding in
powers of :
 
where
 

Here, we consider rolling tachyon field with spatial modulation in
-direction,
 

and, for simplicity, turn off all other components of the gauge
fields but . Then, Eq.() and Eq.() imply
that nonzero components of the energy-momentum tensor  are
 
and nonzero components of the Kalb-Ramond current tensor 
